com.camerontec.util.datamodel

Interface FieldGroup

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Nullable, OrderedCollection<Field>, OrderedCollectionOfFields, OrderedCollectionOfIntKeyed<Field>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    Message
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    MessageImpl, NullFieldGroup, NullMessage

    public interface FieldGroup
extends OrderedCollectionOfFields
    Interface to be implemented by field groups.

    A field group is an ordered collection of fields.

    In terms of lifecycle management, clients must not assume it is safe to store a reference to a FieldGroup (or Field) unless it can be guaranteed that the original owning Message will not be recycled for the duration of storage. The characteristics of FieldGroup lifecycle management are:

    • Each field group is owned by the message from which it was obtained
    • Operations which modify the ordinality of a field group (e.g. removing a prior field group from the same parent Field via OrderedCollection.removeAt(int)) invalidate the field group handle (i.e. this object). It is therefore recommended, in particular for field groups objects, that their usage scope is always localized as much as possible.
    • All field groups conceptually go out of scope when their owning message is recycled, after which time any references stored by client code become dangling and any attempt to use them will result in undefined behavior.

    This interface specializes OrderedCollectionOfFields to allow implementations to use more efficient internal representations and to help clients take advantage of such implementations. In particular, for fields which:

    1. Are added with ByteArrayView values
    2. Are never queried via any method returning Field
    it can be more efficient to only consume Field objects lazily. To help clients take advantage of these implementations methods are provided here which allow direct access to the underlying ByteArrayView values (i.e. without first query for a Field object). Care must therefore be taken not to modify ByteArrayView values directly as this is likely to cause corruption.
    See Also:
    NullFieldGroup, Field, NullField, Message

    • Method Detail

      • getByteArrayView

        ByteArrayView getByteArrayView(int key,
                               ByteArrayView value)
        Return the underlying ByteArrayView value associated with the specified key.

        Note that this is not always possible. If the value has already been queried as a Field then the underlying ByteArrayView will not be returned and the caller must use OrderedCollectionOfFields.get(int) instead.

        Parameters:
        key - The key.
        value - The value.
        Returns:
        The value if the underlying ByteArrayView value is available, null otherwise.

      • getByteArrayViewAt

        ByteArrayView getByteArrayViewAt(int index,
                                 ByteArrayView value)
        Return the underlying ByteArrayView value associated with the specified index.

        Note that this is not always possible. If the value has already been queried as a Field then the underlying ByteArrayView will not be returned and the caller must use OrderedCollectionOfFields.getAt(int) instead.

        Parameters:
        index - The index.
        value - The value.
        Returns:

      • visitDepthFirst

        void visitDepthFirst(BytesFieldVisitor visitor)
        Have all this field groups nested fields visited by the specified visitor.

        Implementations must try to ensure that no additional field objects are consumed and attempt to pass ByteArrayView values to the visitor where possible.

        Where Field object are already consumed then they must take precedence over the underlying ByteArrayView value and be passed to the visitor.

        Parameters:
        visitor - The visitor.

      • visitDepthFirst

        void visitDepthFirst(FieldVisitor visitor)
        Have all this field groups nested fields visited by the specified visitor.

        Note that this method has the side effect of guaranteeing that a Field object is consumed for every field. It is therefore recommended to, if possible, use visitDepthFirst(BytesFieldVisitor) instead.

        Parameters:
        visitor - The visitor.
